Task.Name: Project Management for MS Website
Task.Notes:
The Project Management template plan provides a work breakdown structure that can be used to plan and schedule the effort of the Project Management activities.
The template was built using all the stages, activities and tasks from the Project Management methodology.

Task.Name: Initiating
Task.Notes: The Initiating Stage does the preliminary analysis to define the project objectives and ensures that further project work is authorized.

Task.Name: Develop Project Charter
Task.Notes: The Project Charter is developed to formally authorize a project. The Project Charter contrains the high level definition of the project and the business justification for the project.

Task.Name: Identify Goals and Objectives
Task.Notes: Define the primary goals and objectives for the project.

ExtendedAttribute.Value: Goals and Objectives, List of Constraints

Task.Name: Develop Strategies and Plans
Task.Notes: Understand the business organization and its personnel and formulate high level strategies and plans to ensure achievement of objectives.

Task.Name: Research Previous Experience
Task.Notes: Research previous experience with similar projects and with similar technologies and obtain sample materials.

Task.Name: Develop Project Charter
Task.Notes: Develop the Project Charter and present it for approval to proceed with the project.

Task.Name: Develop Preliminary Project Scope Statement
Task.Notes: The preliminary steps necessary to develop the project's goals and objectives and secure commitment to continue the project.

Task.Name: Conduct Planning Workshop
Task.Notes: Conduct an internal planning session to think through all elements of the project, identify the critical success factors, and map out the project approach.

ExtendedAttribute.Value: Delivery Approach, Meeting Minutes, Action Items

Task.Name: Document Project Costs and Benefits
Task.Notes: Perform the cost/benefit analysis for the projects. Document the cash flows, (i.e., benefits minus costs). Document the benefits and risks that cannot be assigned a cash value.

ExtendedAttribute.Value: Benefit Estimating Worksheets, Cost Estimating Worksheets

Task.Name: Develop High Level Work Breakdown Structure
Task.Notes: Completely identify all of the work to be performed and organize the work into manageable pieces (subprojects).

Task.Name: Conduct Peer Review
Task.Notes: Conduct a peer review session to solicit feedback on the project approach from senior delivery and management personnel from outside the project team.

Task.Name: Prepare Preliminary Project Scope Statement
Task.Notes: Consolidate the preliminary planning material developed into the Preliminary Project Scope Statement

Task.Name: Planning
Task.Notes: The Planning Stage defines the necessary steps to ensure that proper planning is done, during project start-up, before each new phase starts and as part of the change management process

Task.Name: Set Up Project Environment
Task.Notes: Ensure that the fundamental project delivery infrastructure is in place (e.g., work space, standards and procedures, project tools).

Task.Name: Prepare Facilities
Task.Notes: Obtain and furnish work space with the appropriate facilities.

Task.Name: Set Up Project Standards and Procedures
Task.Notes: Define and document the specific standards and procedures to be applied on the project to ensure consistent delivery in accordance with the quality requirements.

ExtendedAttribute.Value: Project Standards and Procedures, Standards and Procedures for Team Performance, Standards and Procedures for General Practices, Standards and Procedures for Meetings, Standards and Procedures for Cost/Schedule Management, Standards and Procedures for Org

Task.Name: Set Up Project Management Tools
Task.Notes: Implement the project management tools to be used by the project team to manage performance.

Task.Name: Set Up Project Book
Task.Notes: Collect and store the project's quality and scope control records in a standard, single location to provide familiar, rapid access to key project management information.

Task.Name: Define Scope
Task.Notes: Establish the Project Scope, WBS and Deliverables necessary to ensure that the objectives defined in the Project Charter are met.

Task.Name: Document Scope Management Plan
Task.Notes: The Scope Management Plan defines the degree of rigor to be applied to the project based on it's size, complexity, risk tolerance and organizational importance.

Task.Name: Specify Deliverables and Acceptance Criteria
Task.Notes: Create a clear and unambiguous definition of each deliverable in terms of format, size and quality requirements, and specify the acceptance procedures and acceptance criteria for each deliverable.

Task.Name: Define Scope
Task.Notes: Establish and maintain a common understanding with the customer of the scope of the project.

Task.Name: Document Assumptions
Task.Notes: Maintain an ongoing list of the assumptions on which the estimates and schedules are based.

Task.Name: Develop Project Schedule
Task.Notes: Identify and assign project resources, determine project activity and task dependencies, develop task estimates develop the project schedule.

Task.Name: Build Work Breakdown Structure
Task.Notes: Develop the project structure in terms of detailed phases, activities, tasks, deliverables, and resources.

Task.Name: Develop Resource Plans
Task.Notes: Identify resources (human and other) that will be required to successfully deliver the project

Task.Name: Prepare Project Estimates
Task.Notes: Produce a detailed estimates of the costs and material resources required to deliver each component of the Work Breakdown Structure.

Task.Name: Define Dependencies and Develop Project Schedule
Task.Notes: Define the milestones and phase dates for each component of the Work Breakdown Structure, and identify the dependencies between the work components (the network logic).

Task.Name: Document Assumptions
Task.Notes: Maintain an ongoing list of the assumptions on which the estimates and schedules are based.

Task.Name: Closing
Task.Notes: Close out the project upon completion.

Task.Name: Close Project
Task.Notes: Make sure that the project is properly closed down, either when project delivery is complete or when the project is terminated for whatever reason.

Task.Name: Assess Satisfaction
Task.Notes: Document the overall satisfaction with the project.

Task.Name: Summarize Project Results and Lessons Learned
Task.Notes: Work with the project team to capture relevant experience and lessons learned for the benefit of future projects.

Task.Name: Review and Recognize Team Performance
Task.Notes: Complete performance reviews for each team member, recognize efforts and accomplishments, and celebrate success.

Task.Name: Close Out the Project Records
Task.Notes: Update and archive project documentation and make sure that all close out conditions have been met.

Task.Name: Review and Reconcile Financial Performance
Task.Notes: Make sure that all invoices have been delivered and all payments made.

Task.Name: Contract Closure
Task.Notes: Blab

Task.Name: Close Contract
Task.Notes: Specific actions required to ensure acceptance of deliverables, process final payments and archive and close out project contract files.

Resource.Name: Project Director
Resource.Notes: Responsible for management of the project at a strategic level.

Resource.Name: Project Manager
Resource.Notes: Responsible for the delivery of a quality project on-schedule, within budget, with a satisfied Acceptor and a motivated project team.

Resource.Name: Acceptor
Resource.Notes: Key individual within the business organization who is the principal interface with the project team and who has the authority to accept all deliverables and resolve all project issues (sometimes referred to as the Project Sponsor).

Resource.Name: Application Architect
Resource.Notes: Defines the major application systems needed to support the enterprise. During systems development, the Application Architect defines the application solution.

Resource.Name: Technical Architect
Resource.Notes: Defines the technologies and standards required to support the application and information architectures. During systems development, the Technical Architect defines the technical solution.

Resource.Name: Quality Assurance Manager
Resource.Notes: Responsible for providing confidence to management that the Quality System is being applied.

Resource.Name: Contracts Manager
Resource.Notes: Responsible for managing the contractual interfaces with the customer and with subcontractors.
